	This is the fourth and last of a series of articles 
designed to be used as a resource or a starting ground in 
determining which alternative/complementary treatment will 
benefit you. Although there are many therapies not addressed, 
you'll find most of the commonly recognized modalities briefly 
described here. Remember, this is a brief description. Often 
we will not be able to do justice to the therapy in question 
in such a limited amount of space. This resource is meant to 
educate you as to the numerous options available. YOU are the 
one who is empowered to take control over your health on a 
going forward basis. Remember, too, that the onus is upon the 
individual to ensure that the practitioner you choose is 
properly qualified and possesses the required certification 
for your area.



Polarity Therapy - According to this principle, a body 
generates both positive and negative energy. Constant 
pulsation from these areas creates energetic lines of 
force... a life energy. Disease occurs when the life 
energy is blocked or out of balance. Typically, too 
much positivity is associated with heat, inflammation, 
irritation and swelling. Too much negative energy is 
associated with tension, spasm, and poor circulation. 

To address these health concerns Polarity Therapy has 
four inter-related therapeutic methods:

Bodywork:  Through gentle touch, the practitioner's 
		hands assist the flow of healing energy 
		in the client's body.

Diet:      Advice on diet and nutrition is given 
		promoting the use of specific dietary 
		principles for internal cleansing.

Exercise:  A specific set of exercises referred to as 
		Polarity Yoga. This series of or self-help 
		energy techniques create relaxation and 
		balance.

Self-Awareness:  Learn to understand the sources of your 
		tension and discover ways to maintain your 
		health.

It is this combination approach and a different energy theory 
which differentiates Polarity Therapy from other similar forms. 


Pranic Healing - Pranic Healing utilizes the life force to 
initiate biochemical changes to allow the body to heal itself. 
Pranic Healing claims to prevent and heal  a whole spectrum of 
physical, emotional and mental ailments using a "no-touch" 
methodology. Because the methods are simple and easy to 
understand, anyone can learn to apply pranic healing.



Reiki - Reiki is a non-invasive hands on healing technique 
which uses the Universal Life-Force Energy to heal. The 
subject plays an active role in the healing process using 
the practitioner to channel positive, healing energy. Reiki 
is said to be helpful on spiritual, mental, emotional and 
physical levels. 


Rolfing- Rolfing was named after its' creator, Ida P. Rolf, 
a biochemist and physical therapist. 
She claims to have found a correlation between muscular 
tension and pent up emotions. Dr. Rolf developed a deep 
tissue massage which surpasses chiropractic in that it is 
based on proper alignment beyond that of the spine. The 
belief is that you must align your head, ankles, hips, 
thorax, pelvis, knees, shoulders, ears, etc., in a specific 
manner or poor physical and/or emotional health will result. 


Reflexology - This treatment is based on the principle that 
there are reflex areas formed by thousands of nerve endings 
in each hand and foot which also correspond to all other 
organs and glands. Proper stimulation of these reflexes is 
a natural way of relieving dis-ease throughout the body and 
maintaining good health. This is a safe, effective, reliable 
process; a non-invasive therapy which can help bring about a 
balance in the body's systems. Especially beneficial in 
dealing with stress, circulation, TMJ, migraines, constipation, 
toxic overload, indigestion, PMS and menstrual concerns, 
allergies, asthma, colds, arthritis, bladder concerns and 
much more.


Shiatsu -  Similar to Acupressure, Shiatsu promotes health 
and vitality by balancing the circulation of vital energy 
which flowing throughout the body along pathways. During a 
theraputic massage, the practitioner applies pressure to 
specific meridian points. This pressure stimulates and 
rebalances the energy flow. In addition, gentle stretching 
techniques are used to release tension from the body and 
improve flexibility. Shiatsu may be of particular benefit 
to conditions such as back pain, migraine, headache, 
toothache, digestive problems, tension, insomnia, anxiety. 


This concludes the therapies that we've covered in this 
series. I hope it's been helpful for you. Take control, 
be empowered, and stay healthy.

