Section 5   	What the cosmetic companies really offer you. 
				Part Two

			By LaNita Wampold 
			mailto:LaNita@LaNita.com

 "My Skin Care Product's Ingredients SOUND Natural"?   

The ingredient lists may be impressive with substances 
beneficial to skin and hair, such as jojoba oil, aloe vera, 
herbal extracts, essential oils. These ingredients are 
unfortunately rendered useless and ineffective by 
synthetic additives.  

To speak further about ingredients in shampoos, shower gels, 
bubbling bath additives, and toothpastes brings us to the 
foaming agents used within them. The foam attacks and 
destroys the skin flora, and the skin becomes even more 
brittle and dry. This is made apparent by the itching that 
then must be relieved with a moisturizing lotion or cream. 
To compensate for this negative effect manufacturers add 
oils or fats to replace those lost due to the active 
cleansing substances. The question then becomes: Why are 
such aggressive substances used to begin with? The answer 
is: Because "Squeaky Clean", is what advertising has 
proclaimed for decades as being of utmost importance.   

The same consequences apply to the chemical dyes and fragrances 
contained  in many products. Since synthetic cosmetics don't have 
a pleasing color or  smell, they must be "doctored" to appeal to 
the eye and nose of the consumer; thus the addition of further 
chemicals to mask the base ingredients. Also, the production of 
an emulsifier from water and oil--the  basis of almost all creams, 
lotions, and shampoos-- is possible only with an emulsifying agent 
or thickener. 

Because of their cost, natural emulsifying agents and thickeners 
are not used. The chemical emulsifying agents that are used 
instead impair the effectiveness of the natural substances or 
attack the flora. The problem is even more serious in lipsticks. 
The thin, unprotected skin of the mouth is directly affected by 
dyes, which enter into the body and affect the metabolism. 
Similarly, mascaras, eye shadows, and eyeliners contain heavy 
metals and chemical dyes that penetrate the skin. These metals and
dyes are stored on a long-term basis in the body, and poison it.   

"My Skin Care Says It Will Reverse Wrinkles":   

Among the above list are the moisturizing creams and lotions 
made of water and mineral oils that "provide" the upper 
layer of the skin with moisture for some hours and then 
puzzelingly cause it to dry out. Anti-wrinkle or anti- aging 
creams that temporarily cause the surface skin to swell, are
very popular. The skin looks smooth, fresh and younger for 
several hours, but soon falls back into its old condition.   

These "wonder drug" substances the creams contain--collagen,  
elastin, and the like--smooth the skin and give a temporary 
impression of improvement--until the next time the face is 
washed. In fact, once the natural collagen and elastin in the  
connective tissue has attained an age-appropriate, hardened  
condition wrinkles cannot be "ironed-out". What is possible 
at this time is to stimulate the formation of new skin cells 
and to discourage the further loss of moisture.   

Many cosmetics have promised "wondrous" effects and have been 
offered over the past  few decades: liposome, vitamins, collagen,
elastin, and hormones. Yet the  condition of people's skin has 
not improved. The consumer increasingly suffers from eczema, 
itching and irritations of the skin, dryness, extreme oiliness, 
and damaged skin flora--symptoms that are widely influenced by 
aggressive, synthetic cleansing and skin care agents.   

What about "Hypo-allergenic"?  

Finally, let me speak about the promise of hypo-allergenic 
products offered on the market. "Allergy-tested" means only 
that the product was tested, it does not tell us what the 
tests results were. The very fact that it had to be tested 
should be enough to cause concern.   

It is widely known that the tests conducted by cosmetic 
manufacturers are based on animal experiments that take the 
life of over one  hundred million animals a year. The animals 
are injected or forced to ingest substances, or have substances 
sprayed into their eyes or applied to their skin.   

Even the "positive results" obtained by this testing cannot 
guarantee cosmetics without side effects. As consumers, we 
are not told that the "positive" results were extremely 
positive or merely barely tolerable. Often the long-term 
effect of some toxic or carcinogenic substance in a cosmetic 
product is discovered only after many years.
